tGlossary of Names -- tGlossary of Places -- tGlossary of Realia -- tBibliography -- tFurther Reading -- tIndex of Qurʾanic Verses -- tIndex of Arabic Verses -- tIndex -- tAbout the NYU Abu Dhabi Institute -- tAbout the Typefaces -- tAbout the Editor and Translators0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConsorts of the Caliphs is a seventh/thirteenth-century compilation of anecdotes about thirty-eight women who were, as the title suggests, consorts to those in power, most of them concubines of the early Abbasid caliphs and wives of latter-day caliphs and sultans. This slim but illuminating volume is one of the few surviving texts by Ibn al-Sa'i (d. 674/1276). Ibn al-Sa'i was a prolific Baghdadi scholar who chronicled the academic and political elites of his city, and whose career straddled the final years of the Abbasid dynasty and the period following the cataclysmic Mongol invasion of 656/1258.In this work, Ibn al-Sa'i is keen to forge a connection between the munificent wives of his time and the storied lovers of the so-called golden age of Baghdad. Thus, from the earlier period, we find Harun al-Rashid pining for his brother’s beautiful slave, Ghadir, and the artistry of such musical and literary celebrities as 'Arib and Fadl, who bested the male poets and singers of their day. From times closer to Ibn al-Sa'i’s own—when Abbasid authority was trying to reassert itself and Baghdad was again a major center of intellectual and religious activity—we meet women such as Banafsha, who endowed law colleges, had bridges built, and provisioned pilgrims bound for Mecca; slave women whose funeral services were led by caliphs; and noble Saljuq princesses from Afghanistan.Informed by the author’s own sources, his insider knowledge, and well-known literary materials, these singular biographical sketches, though delivered episodically, bring the belletristic culture of the Baghdad court to life, particularly in the personal narratives and poetry of culture heroines otherwise lost to history.A bilingual Arabic-English edition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAbbasidsvEarly works to 1800. 0aIslamic EmpirexHistoryy750-1258vEarly works to 1800. 0aQueenszIslamic EmpirexAnecdotesvEarly works to 1800. 0aWomenzIslamic EmpirexAnecdotesvEarly works to 1800. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh1 aBray, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiterature, The Editors of the Library of Arabic, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToorawa, Shawkat M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToorawa, Shawkat M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWarner, Marina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479879045.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479879045423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479879045/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles